-- ARM Holdings Plc, BAE, BP, Provident Financial: U.K., Irish Equity Preview
-- Ben Martin
-- 2010-07-26T23:00:00Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-26/arm-holdings-plc-bae-bp-provident-financial-u-k-irish-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following is a list of companies
whose shares may have unusual price changes in U.K. and Irish
markets. Stock symbols are in parentheses and prices are from
the last market close.  
 The benchmark  FTSE 100 Index  rose 38.50, or 0.7 percent, to
5,351.12. The  FTSE All-Share Index  also advanced 0.7 percent and
Ireland’s  ISEQ Index  climbed 1 percent.  
 ARM Holdings Plc  (ARM LN): The designer of semiconductors
used in Apple Inc.’s iPhone is due to report first-half
earnings. The shares fell 2 percent to 346.1 pence.  
 BAE Systems Plc  (BA/ LN): Europe’s largest defense company
was hired by Aquamarine Power Ltd., a U.K. wave energy
developer, to help design and build components to reduce the
cost of its marine-energy device. The stock rose 0.1 percent to
316.9 pence.  
 BP Plc  (BP/ LN):  Robert Dudley  will be named to succeed
 Tony Hayward  as BP’s chief executive officer as the board
looks to recover the company’s position in the U.S., two people
with knowledge of the matter said. Hayward will be offered a
role at the company’s Russian joint venture, Sky News reported.
The shares advanced 4.6 percent to 416.95 pence.  
 Croda International Plc  (CRDA LN): The U.K. supplier of sun
block agents to Procter & Gamble Co. is scheduled to report
first-half earnings. The stock rose 0.2 percent to 1,173 pence.  
 Informa Plc  (INF LN): The U.K. publisher of Lloyd’s List is
due to report first-half earnings. The shares advanced 1.7
percent to 387.6 pence.  
 Provident Financial Plc  (PFG LN): The U.K.’s biggest
subprime lender is due to report first-half earnings. The stock
rose 0.8 percent to 882.5 pence.  
 PZ Cussons Plc  (PZC LN): The U.K. maker of Imperial Leather
soap is scheduled to report earnings. The shares declined 1.9
percent to 360 pence.  
 Xstrata Plc  (XTA LN): The biggest exporter of coal for
power stations is due to release its first-half production
report. The stock climbed 0.2 percent to 1,036.5 pence.  
 To contact the reporter on this story:
